        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging: ALMA Band 3 currently provides the largest FOV most suitable for a quasi-blind survey such as that proposed here. In order to cover the core of the protocluster and the SMG, we define 5 pointings. We have optimised their positions so as to maximise the number of photo-z cluster member candidates also falling within the survey footprint. This permits coverage of 104 sources (95 photometric, 8 spectroscopic, 1 SMG) within the 4.1 sq. arcmin covered, in addition to serendipitous sources not featured in the source catalogue. Because we are not seeking to resolve emission within in the target galaxies, we request seeing of 1 arcsecond; emission will be point-source like, meaning no issues arise from the maximum recoverable scale. Nevertheless, some (photometric) sources will blend at poorer angular resolutions: 1 arcsecond offers the best compromise between availability of array configurations and source blending.

Sensitivity: We aim to detect CO(3-2) line emission (345.8GHz rest-frame) from the spectroscopically confirmed protocluster members. Because these have not been detected as SMG sources, and with the limited observational data available for similar such targets, we use line emission predictions from the Lagos et al. (2012) model, based on UCL_PDR. That study presents a candidate (BzK+gal4) with similar SFR, stellar mass and BzK index to those detected for the spectroscopic members. BzK+gal4 has a peak CO(3-2) line flux of 1.03mJy. We rescale this, assuming only cosmological evolution to the z=2.44 detection redshift, and see a 3-sigma line detection that requires sensitivity of 0.32mJy. This sensitivity is very much in line with the broad CO(3-2) line emission of the ``Cosmic Eyelash'' (Danielson 2011), which would be detected at a significance of 2-sigma. The SMG, with an SFR at least 2 orders of magnitude more than those at our sensitivity limit, will be unambiguously detected in CO(3-2) at this sensitivity should it fall within the redshift range of the protocluster. 

Correlator: Correlators have been tuned to maximise bandwidth coverage within the sidebands. We opt for FDM multiplexing, covering 1.875GHz. The baseband covering the redshifted CO(3-2) line is centered according to a z=2.4 source, and is adequate in bandwidth to encapsulate shifting of this line according to the redshift distribution of cluster members. Within the galaxies we target, the spectral line widths may vary from between 100-850km/s To balance our sensitivity requirements, we stipulate velocity bins of 150km/s - sufficient to accurately resolve and fit the broadest line profiles, yet narrow enough to sample narrower lines without risking blending of different spectral features. Due to data bandwidth constraints, we set the spectral averaging to 2 in each baseband. Given our requested spectral sensitivity, this does not impact our aims of identifiying broad spectral lines.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
